column5: Two issues were identified. The MES system does not appear to be updating EP as quicklyl as anticipated. There is nothing that this group can do about that issue. The other issue, however, appears to deal with how the system determines who should get the back to green emails. When presented with a workstation that changed its status to production', it would find the last event that was of type production', setup', or other downtime'. The back to green mail was sent to all user's that had been notified by the system between these two events. However, the stamping presses frequently cycle from a repair state to a setup state and then to production. In this situation, the software would not send any notifications since its last good state was the setup that preceeded the return to production. The system has been modified to only consider production as a valid previous state. With this change, all personnel that were notified of an issue between the current event and the previous production event will be notified that the workstation is back in production.

column5: PROBLEM DESCRIPTION The ECC report ZPMABE, and the BW target act. comparison setup min. report, were showing incorrect changeover setup time. PROBLEM CAUSE When BW extract was taken from ECC, the table ZPP RUESTZT in ECC was not updated for this material. PROBLEM SOLUTION Program ZAP RUESTMTX GEN runs as batch job every night at am and updates table ZPP RUESTZT. The day after opening this ticket, the table was updated, and BW extract included that data so both the reports now shows correct changeover setup time. It was basically a timing issue. PROBLEM WORKAROUND N A

column5: Group policy was not being applied to the machine and further investigation showed that no network resources were accessible. No UNC paths, no DFS paths, nothing. Machine was accessible on the network, able to resolve and ping network resources but simply unable to connect to the resources. Event log showed that the TCP IP NetBIOS Helper service was unable to start. Looking at the services on the machine, the service was listed but the description couldn't be found so this appeared to be the root of the problem. Uninstalled Client for Microsoft Networks from the NIC, rebooted PC, and the TCP IP NetBIOS service was properly removed. Reinstalled the client for MS networks on the NIC but the service wasn't returned. Further investigation showed that the lmhsvc.dll file in the system directory appeared to be corrupt information on the details tab of this file were missing. This file was copied from a working machine but service still didn't appear after a reboot. To restore the service, the HKEY LOCAL MACHINEkey was copied from a known working machine and imported to After rebooting the service was running properly. When Mr. Snepp attempted to log on, he was presented with a black desktop background, but no taskbar and no icons. Only the Windows identifier in the lower right corner of the screen and the mouse pointer. CTRLALTDEL would not work, it was not possible to log off or restart. Rebooted the PC, and renamed the profile for Mr. Snepp using KB and after doing this, Mr. Snepp was able to log in normally.
